Runs `cargo-machete` to fail the build on unused Cargo dependencies, as one static check among several template scripts (alongside `cycle_check.sh`) invoked in an offline CI context.

Requires `cargo-machete` to be installed; a missing binary is a hard `FAIL` (exit 1), not a skip — unlike checks that need network/`cargo metadata` (e.g. `cargo deny`), this one is expected to always be runnable offline, so silently skipping would make ctx-verify's pass misleading.

Non-obvious behavior: `cargo machete` exits non-zero both for "found unused deps" and for real errors, so the script always captures output first (`rc=$?`), then parses it with `awk` to emit one `FAIL: <path> unused dependency '<dep>'` line per finding. The awk parser depends on cargo-machete's exact report shape — a header line `<crate> -- <path/Cargo.toml>:` followed by tab-indented dependency names; if that format changes, findings silently stop being reported even though `rc` may still be nonzero (guarded by the fallback below).

If `cargo machete` exits nonzero but the awk parse produced zero FAIL lines (e.g. it couldn't read a manifest), the script emits a generic `FAIL: cargo machete failed` line so the error is never swallowed. Exit code is `$FAIL` (0 or 1), independent of the raw `rc`.